nings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Ledrede was born in 1465, in London, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Deledrede, was 50 and his mother, Mrs. Thomas Deledrede, was 41. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Richard Ledrede."},"et":{"1465–":"1465–Surnud","1465–Male":"1465–Surnud","1470–Female":"1470–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1501–Male":"1501–Surnud","1415–Male":"1415–Surnud","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1501":"1501","1465":"1465","1470":"1470","England":"England","London, England":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1465–":"1465–Kuollut","1465–Male":"1465–Kuollut","1470–Female":"1470–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1501–Male":"1501–Kuollut","1415–Male":"1415–Kuollut","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1501":"1501","1465":"1465","1470":"1470","England":"England","London, England":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1465–":"1465–Décédé","1465–Male":"1465–Décédé","1470–Female":"1470–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1501–Male":"1501–Décédé","1415–Male":"1415–Décédé","1425–Female":"1425–Décédée","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1501":"1501","1465":"1465","1470":"1470","England":"Angleterre","London, England":"Londres, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Richard Ledrede est né en 1465, à Londres, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Thomas Deledrede, avait 50 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Thomas Deledrede, avait 41 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs. Richard Ledrede."},"de":{"1465–":"1465–Verstorben","1465–Male":"1465–Verstorben","1470–Female":"1470–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1501–Male":"1501–Verstorben","1415–Male":"1415–Verstorben","1425–Female":"1425–Verstorben","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1501":"1501","1465":"1465","1470":"1470","En